Working Life

The story of how the Chinese Candadians found work after the CPR work ended.

  • Next

Summary

Chinese Canadians encountered major difficulties in securing jobs following the conclusion of the CPR project in Canada. Consequently, a considerable number of them were left unemployed and without many viable alternatives. Despite a lack of job opportunities, many Chinese Canadians found themselves in canaries and farms, providing significantly to the community. The document highlights how those two jobs were very important, as they were necessary jobs that many people relied on.

Stuck in Canada

The Chinese people brought to Canada to work on the railway were promised a return ship fare by Andrew Onderdonk after the work ended, but that was not provided for them. Many of them could not afford a trip back, so they had to find work quickly after the CPR work ended.

Canning Fish

Working in canaries was unpleasant work, as it was smelly, especially in summer, and it involved lots of labour work. When the Iron Chink machine was invented, on one hand, it greatly improved the production rate of the canned fish, however, it also took many of the Chinese Canadians jobs away, and they were once again left with no work.

Farm Markets

Working farms was a very significant job to the economy of BC, as the farm markets provided much of the fresh produce for Vancouver and Victoria, as well as other smaller cities and towns. The Chinese Canadians who worked on these farms produced fresh produce, developed markets, and provided for many people, showing their great marketing, farming, and entrepreneurship skills. Working on these farms, they also connected with the First Nations community, creating close relationships.
